TION (TAḤRĪQ) BETWEEN THE ISLAMIC STATE AND AL-QĀ ʿIDA -- tPart IV. Communicating Violence -- t12. VIOLENCE AND POLITICAL MOBILISATION IN THE DISCOURSE OF MUQTADĀ AL-ṢADR -- t13. MANAGING VIOLENT CONFLICT: HUDNA AND TAHDIʾA, BEYOND A STRATEGIC PAUSE -- t14. NOTES ON SOME JIHADIST POEMS -- t15. THE ‘OTHER’ IN THE DISCOURSE OF HAMAS AND HIZBULLAH -- t16. CONCLUDING REMARKS: VIOLENCE IN ISLAMIC THOUGHT -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores Muslim attitudes towards violence from the 19th century to the present dayExamines perceptions and expressions of violence in a wide range of contexts in the modern period: Algeria, Afghanistan, Egypt, India, Iraq, Israel, Libya, Nigeria, Palestine, Syria, Tunisia and Yemen Shows the nuances behind headline-making events and organisations such as al-Qaeda, the Taliban, Islamic State, Salafi jihadism, the Mahdi Army, Hamas, Hezbollah and the Arab RevolutionsEngages with key figures including Fażl-i Ḥaqq Khayrābādī, Ahmad Riza Khan, Muqtadá al-Ṣadr, Muḥammad al-Maqdisi, Ayman al-Ẓawāhirī and Turkī al-BinʿAlīEnables a more informed understanding of the nature of violence in the modern period, in the Muslim world and beyondMuslim attitudes toward violence have been reshaped in light of the colonial context since the 18th and 19th centuries, and in response to regional and world-changing events of the contemporary period. This volume shows the diversity of approaches to violence in Islamic thought, avoiding the limiting characterisations of Islam being inherently ‘violent’ or ‘peaceful’.It shows how ideas of ‘justified violence’ – grounded in Islamic theological and juristic traditions – reoccur throughout history, up to the contemporary period. Chapters on earlier events provide context for contemporary debates on violence, showing how traditional legal and theological ideas (such as the sovereignty of God’s law and peace treaties) are used to both legitimise and de-legitimise violence.Violence in Islamic Thought from European Imperialism to the Post-Colonial Era is the final volume in the Violence in Islamic Thought trilogy. Taken together, the three books cover key aspects of violence in Islamic thought from the earliest time to the present day, mapping a trajectory of thinking about violence over 14 centuries of Islamic history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aViolencezIslamxReligious aspects. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aAlshaer, Atef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnchassi, Omar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaig, Mustafa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElibiary, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallois, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhyoot, Mathias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleave, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGleave, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartung, Jan-Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHámori, András, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhosrokhavar, Farhad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLav, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawrence, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilton-Edwards, Beverley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRizvi, Sajjad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWagemakers, Joas, econt